&gt; Speaking of lists, how can this notation be expanded for use in
testing
&gt; lists?  While Hamcrest&#39;s current support for lists seems somewhat
&gt; spotty-I haven&#39;t used it too, too much so I could be wrong-it has the
&gt; capability to be expanded to provide robust support for lists.  Using
a
&gt; Hamcrest-like notation, NUnit allows you to say things like this:
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Assert.That( iarray, Has.No.Null );

With JUnit&#39;s matchers, this can be

assertThat(iarray, each(notNullValue());

&gt; Assert.That( iarray, Is.Unique );

I&#39;m not aware of a built-in matcher for this one, but it could be
written.

&gt; Assert.That( iarray, Has.All.GreaterThan(0) );

With the full hamcrest library and JUnit:

assertThat(iarray, each(greaterThan(0)));

&gt; Assert.That( iarray, Has.Some.GreaterThan(2) );

assertThat(iarray, hasItem(greaterThan(2)));

&gt; You&#39;ll notice that in this case, we are mixing matchers (Is/Has,
&gt; All/No/Some, GreaterThan, and Null) in order to test this list using
&gt; matchers that are not named after functions on the list under test.
&gt; You&#39;ll also notice that the mixing of the matchers allows us to
produce
&gt; rather powerful combinations that are not necessarily foreseen by the
&gt; JUnit developers.  Will this new notation support such extensions as
&gt; well?

I guess it could, but I&#39;m not sure yet it should. The typing gets
rough. Continued thoughts appreciated.

